Hi Bob,

Thank you for the thoughtful reply.

You are getting to the exact point that usually determines whether a 
custom system is actually viable long term or simply becomes another 
dependency with a different label.

Our approach is generally built around two principles: strong isolation 
at the architecture level, and structured change management after 
handoff.

On the isolation side, we do not rely on a single pattern universally. 
The right design depends on the risk profile, operational model, and 
expected scale of the system. In cases where boundaries are critical, we 
prefer enforcing them as close to the data layer as practical, with the 
application layer complementing that rather than carrying the full 
burden alone. The goal is to make separation a property of the system 
itself, not just a convention in business logic.

On the evolution side, we try to avoid creating systems where every 
meaningful change has to route back through the original builder. We 
usually structure delivery so that schema changes, workflow adjustments, 
and rule updates can be managed in a controlled way by the client's 
team, with proper versioning, migration discipline, and documentation in 
place. Where requirements are likely to evolve, we also try to keep 
volatile logic abstracted from the underlying structure so the system 
can adapt without unnecessary rewiring.

The broader idea is that post handoff should not feel like loss of 
control. It should feel like ownership with a clear operating model.

Given your background, I imagine that is probably the real filter for 
you not whether something can be built, but whether it remains 
predictable once it is no longer sitting with the original team.

Happy to unpack how we usually think about that design boundary in more 
detail with the relevant technical bench from our side so the 
conversation stays concrete and useful.

Happy to work around your calendar for a discussion later next week.

